         <div type="translation">
            <p>
               <choice corresp="#a1">
                  <seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>297</citedRange></bibl></seg>
                  <seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>175</citedRange></bibl></seg>
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">... Who else could have that ability?</seg></seg>
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">Zum Heile der Welt hat dein Geist niemals verzagt.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">To the benefit of the world your spirit has never quailed.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>159</citedRange></bibl></seg>
               </choice>
               <choice corresp="#a1 #a2">
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">Who else could have that ability?</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>303</citedRange></bibl></seg>
               </choice>
               <choice corresp="#a2">
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">If [when] you first left the body of [your]</seg></seg>
               </choice>
               <choice corresp="#a2 #a3 #b1">
                  <seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>175, 234</citedRange></bibl></seg>
                  <seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1954"/><citedRange>719</citedRange></bibl></seg>
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">If [when] you first left the body of [your] mother, you have roared friendship (maitrī) for the benefit of all, and if you have sought to understand the seed of the sorrows, then you have achieved happiness, the ultimate of the virtues.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>380</citedRange></bibl></seg>
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">Als du zuerst aus dem Leib der Mutter herausgegangen bist und [als] du freundschaftliche Gesinnung zum Heil aller gebrüllt hast und als du den Samen(?) der Leiden zu erkennen gesucht hast, [da] hast du dadurch das Glück, das Höchste [wtl. das Ende, Ziel] aller Tugenden, erwirkt.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">When you first went forth from the body of [your] mother and [when] you roared fair-mindedness for the salvation of all and when you tried to perceive the seed(?) of suffering, [then] by this you effected happiness, the [ultimate] end of all virtue.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>98</citedRange></bibl></seg>
               </choice>
               <choice corresp="#a3">
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">mother, you have roared friendship (<hi>maitrī</hi>) for the benefit of all, and if you have sought</seg></seg>
               </choice>
               <choice corresp="#b1">
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">to understand the seed of the sorrows, then you have achieved happiness, the ultimate of the virtues.</seg></seg>
               </choice>
               <choice corresp="#b2 #b3">
                  <seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>198</citedRange></bibl></seg>
                  <seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>175</citedRange></bibl></seg>
                  <seg><seg type="prim_transl">Du hast Leid ertragen, [aber] von [deinem] Entschluss, die Welt von den Leiden zu erlösen, hast du dich, wo auch immer, nicht [fort]bewegt [d.h. bist du nicht abgewichen].</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">You have borne suffering, [but] wherever [you have been], you have not moved [i.e. you have not turned away] from [your] decision to redeem the world from suffering.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>277</citedRange></bibl></seg>
               </choice>
            </p>
